hest_index // len(high_columns) # Determine the row (0 or 1) where the highest value is found lowest_row = lowest_index // len(low_columns) # Determine the row (0 or 1) where the lowest value is found # Determine y_Priority based on the positions and rules given if highest_row < lowest_row: df.at[index, 'y_Priority'] = 1 elif highest_row > lowest_row: df.at[index, 'y_Priority'] = 0 else: # If both are in the same row, determine priority based on the 'numerical' part of the column identifier highest_col = highest_index % len(high_columns) lowest_col = lowest_index % len(low_columns) df.at[index, 'y_Priority'] = 1 if highest_col < lowest_col else 0 # Save the modified DataFrame to a new CSV file df.to_csv('modified_file.csv', index=False) # The data now includes y_High, y_Low, and y_Priority. \`\`\` This version of the code applies a more precise approach to selecting the columns for \`y_High\`, \`y_Low\`, and \`y_Priority\` calculations. It explicitly identifies the correct columns using pattern matching when defining \`high_columns\` and \`low_columns\`, thus avoiding any potential mismatches with other unrelated columns. Again, please ensure the CSV file path is correctly adjusted in your code."},{"instruction":"there is a problem it calculate new columns just for first row and not others","output":"To address the issue you're experiencing, where calculation of the new columns (\`y_High\`, \`y_Low\`, \`y_Priority\`) only occurs for the first row instead of being applied across all applicable rows, let's revise the code snippet to ensure it iterates through and performs the calculations for each applicable row correctly. The previous guidance aimed to correct for precise column selection but might have contained an oversight in ensuring consistent application across the DataFrame. Below, you will find a refined version that rectifies this and ensures the calculations extend across all rows, barring the last two due to the stated logic requiring data from subsequent 